title: Recalibrating the predicitions of an ANN.
text: calibration model can evaluated comparing observed values respective estimated conditional (predictive) distributions. evaluation can conducted globally, examining overall calibration, locally, investigating calibration specific parts covariate space. better illustrate package can improve models’s calibration, let’s consider artificial examples. following example, going recalibrate predictions artificial neural network (ANN) model non-linear heteroscedastic data. First simulate data follows: define sample size: \[\begin{equation} n = 10000 \end{equation}\] vectors \(x_1\) \(x_2\) generated uniform distributions: \[\begin{equation} x_1 \sim \text{Uniform}(-3, 3) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} x_2 \sim \text{Uniform}(-5, 5) \end{equation}\] define function \(\mu\) : \[\begin{equation} \mu(x) = \left| x_1^3 - 50 \sin(x_2) + 30 \right| \end{equation}\] response variable \(y\) generated normal distribution mean \(\mu\) standard deviation \(20 \left| \frac{x_2}{x_1 + 10} \right|\): \[\begin{equation} y \sim \mathcal{N}\left(\mu, 20 \left| \frac{x_2}{x_1 + 10} \right|\right) \end{equation}\] code bellow generates data described . Now, toy model trained using Keras framework TensorFlow backend. ANN architecture consist ANN 3 hidden layers ReLU activation functions dropout regularization follows:
code: library(recalibratiNN) set.seed(42)   # The Answer to the Ultimate Question of Life, The Universe, and Everything  n <- 10000  x <- cbind(x1 = runif(n, -3, 3),            x2 = runif(n, -5, 5))  mu_fun <- function(x) {   abs(x[,1]^3 - 50*sin(x[,2]) + 30)}  mu <- mu_fun(x) y <- rnorm(n,             mean = mu,             sd=20*(abs(x[,2]/(x[,1]+ 10))))  split1 <- 0.6 split2 <- 0.8  x_train <- x[1:(split1*n),] y_train <- y[1:(split1*n)]  x_cal  <- x[(split1*n+1):(n*split2),] y_cal  <- y[(split1*n+1):(n*split2)]  x_test <- x[(split2*n+1):n,] y_test  <- y[(split2*n+1):n] model_nn <- keras_model_sequential()  model_nn |>    layer_dense(input_shape=2,               units=800,               use_bias=T,               activation = "relu",               kernel_initializer="random_normal",               bias_initializer = "zeros") %>%   layer_dropout(rate = 0.1) %>%   layer_dense(units=800,               use_bias=T,               activation = "relu",               kernel_initializer="random_normal",               bias_initializer = "zeros") |>    layer_dropout(rate = 0.1) |>    layer_dense(units=800,               use_bias=T,               activation = "relu",               kernel_initializer="random_normal",               bias_initializer = "zeros") |>     layer_batch_normalization() |>    layer_dense(units = 1,               activation = "linear",               kernel_initializer = "zeros",               bias_initializer = "zeros")  model_nn |>    compile(optimizer=optimizer_adam( ),     loss = "mse")  model_nn |>    fit(x = x_train,        y = y_train,       validation_data = list(x_cal, y_cal),       callbacks = callback_early_stopping(         monitor = "val_loss",         patience = 20,         restore_best_weights = T),       batch_size = 128,       epochs = 1000)   y_hat_cal <- predict(model_nn, x_cal) y_hat_test <- predict(model_nn, x_test)

Similarly, observe miscalibration :  Since example consists bidimensional data, visualize calibration model surface representing covariate space. graph, used 95% Confidence Interval centered mean predicted model, fixed variance estimated Mean Squared Error (MSE). true value falls within interval, colored greenish; falls outside, colored red. following graph illustrates original coverage model, around 90%. code: ## Global calibrations pit <- PIT_global(ycal = y_cal,                    yhat = y_hat_cal,                    mse = MSE_cal)  gg_PIT_global(pit) gg_CD_global(pit,               ycal = y_cal,      # true response of calibration set              yhat = y_hat_cal,  # predictions of calibration set              mse = MSE_cal)    # mse from training on calibration set pit_local <- PIT_local(xcal = x_cal,                        ycal = y_cal,                         yhat = y_hat_cal,                         mse = MSE_cal                        )  gg_PIT_local(pit_local) gg_CD_local(pit_local) coverage_model <- tibble(   x1cal = x_test[,1],    x2cal = x_test[,2],   y_real = y_test,    y_hat = y_hat_test) |>  mutate(lwr = qnorm(0.05, y_hat, sqrt(MSE_cal)),        upr = qnorm(0.95, y_hat, sqrt(MSE_cal)),        CI = ifelse(y_real <= upr & y_real >= lwr,                         "in",  "out" ),        coverage = round(mean(CI == "in")*100,1)  )  coverage_model |>    arrange(CI) |>      ggplot() +   geom_point(aes(x1cal,                   x2cal,                   color = CI),              alpha = 0.9,              size = 2)+    labs(x="x1" , y="x2",          title = glue("Original coverage: {coverage_model$coverage[1]} %"))+   scale_color_manual("Confidence Interval",                      values = c("in" = "aquamarine3",                                  "out" = "steelblue4"))+   theme_classic()

calculated earlier.     space_new = x_test,    # covariates of test set     mse = MSE_cal,         # MSE from calibration set     type = "local",        # type of calibration     p_neighbours = 0.08) cluster_means_cal <- kmeans(x_test, n_clusters)$centers  cluster_means_cal <- cluster_means_cal[order(cluster_means_cal[,1]),]     # finding neighbours knn_cal <- nn2(x_test,                 cluster_means_cal,                 k = n_neighbours)$nn.idx   # geting corresponding ys (real and estimated) y_real_local <- map(1:nrow(knn_cal),  ~y_test[knn_cal[.,]])  y_hat_local <- map(1:nrow(knn_cal),  ~y_hat_rec[knn_cal[.,],])   # calculate pit_local pits <- matrix(NA,                 nrow = 6,                 ncol = n_neighbours)  for (i in 1:n_clusters) {     pits[i,] <- map_dbl(1:n_neighbours, ~{       mean(y_hat_local[[i]][.,] <= y_hat_local[[i]][.])     }) }  as.data.frame(t(pits)) |>    pivot_longer(everything()) |>    group_by(name) |>   mutate(p_value =ks.test(value,                           "punif")$p.value,          name = gsub("V", "part_", name)) |>    ggplot()+   geom_density(aes(value,                    color = name,                    fill = name),                alpha = 0.5,                bounds = c(0, 1))+   geom_hline(yintercept = 1,               linetype="dashed")+   scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set2")+ title: Quantile Recalibration for Regression Models
text: example illustrates common issue miscalibration. demonstrate , created heteroscedastic model fitted using simple linear regression visualization purposes. graph , can observe true mean, data points, regression line. linear model, represented dashed black line, consistently underestimates mean small large values x. Additionally, overestimates variance lower values x, indicated points falling within confidence interval (CI). Conversely, higher values x, model underestimates true variance. discrepancies highlight model’s inability accurately quantify uncertainty, showcasing example miscalibrated model. Model coverage, true mean (red) estimated mean (black dashed line).
code: ## basic artificial model example   set.seed(42) n <- 42000 split <- 0.8  # Auxiliary functions mu <- function(x1){ 10 + 5*x1^2 }  sigma_v <- function(x1){ 30*x1 }  # generating heterocedastic data (true model)  x <- runif(n, 1, 10) y <- rnorm(n,mu(x), sigma_v(x))   # slipting data  x_train <- x[1:(n*split)] y_train <- y[1:(n*split)]  x_cal <- x[(n*split+1):n] y_cal <- y[(n*split+1):n]  # fitting a simple linear model model <- lm(y_train ~ x_train) pacman::p_load(tidyverse) pacman::p_load_gh("AllanCameron/geomtextpath")  # use predict to get the confidence intervals data_predict <- predict(model,                          newdata=data.frame(x_train=x_cal),                          interval = "prediction") %>%    as_tibble() %>%    dplyr::mutate(x_cal=x_cal,                  y_cal=y_cal,           CI=ifelse(y_cal<=upr&y_cal>=lwr, "in", "out"))   data_predict %>%    ggplot(aes(x_cal))+   geom_point(mapping=aes(x_cal, y_cal, color=CI), alpha=0.6)+   geom_labelline(aes( y=mu(x_cal), label="True Mean" ),                   size=1.8, hjust=-0.01, linewidth=0.7, color="red" )+   geom_smooth(aes( y=y_cal ), color="black",se=F,                    method="lm", formula=y~x,linetype="dashed" )+   scale_color_manual("IC 95%", values=c("#00822e", "#2f1d86"))+   theme_classic()
